of Enclosures: A Critique of Internationalization -- t16. The Historian’s Use of the United States and Vice Versa -- tAPPENDIX. Participants in the La Pietra Conferences, 1997–2000 -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn rethinking and reframing the American national narrative in a wider context, the contributors to this volume ask questions about both nationalism and the discipline of history itself. The essays offer fresh ways of thinking about the traditional themes and periods of American history. By locating the study of American history in a transnational context, they examine the history of nation-making and the relation of the United States to other nations and to transnational developments. What is now called globalization is here placed in a historical context.A cast of distinguished historians from the United States and abroad examines the historiographical implications of such a reframing and offers alternative interpretations of large questions of American history ranging from the era of European contact to democracy and reform, from environmental and economic development and migration experiences to issues of nationalism and identity. But the largest issue explored is basic to all histories: How does one understand, teach, and write a national history even as one recognizes that the territorial boundaries do not fully contain that history and that within that bounded territory the society is highly differentiated, marked by multiple solidarities and identities?Rethinking American History in a Global Age advances an emerging but important conversation marked by divergent voices, many of which are represented here. The various essays explore big concepts and offer historical narratives that enrich the content and context of American history. The aim is to provide a history that more accurately reflects the dimensions of American experience and better connects the past with contemporary concerns for American identity, structures of power, and world presence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGlobalization. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh1 aBender, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBender, Thomas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBright, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuara, Prasenjit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFluck, Winfried, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeyer, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoerder, Dirk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHollinger, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIriye, Akira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelley, Robin D. G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKroes, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKupperman, Karen Ordahl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobin, Ron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRodgers, Daniel T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTyrrell, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeil, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWiebe, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYoung, Marilyn B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gru